{"title_page": "Edward Rowan Finnegan", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{other people|Edward Finnegan}}\n{{no footnotes|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Edward Rowan Finnegan\n|image         = Edward Rowan Finnegan.jpg\n|caption       = \n|state1        = [[Illinois]]\n|district1     = {{ushr|Illinois|9|9th}}\n|term_start1   = January 3, 1963\n|term_end1     = December 6, 1964\n|predecessor1  = [[Sidney R. Yates]]\n|successor1    = [[Sidney R. Yates]]\n|state2        = [[Illinois]]\n|district2     = {{ushr|Illinois|12|12th}}\n|term_start2   = January 3, 1961\n|term_end2     = January 3, 1963\n|predecessor2  = [[Charles A. Boyle]]\n|successor2    = [[Robert McClory]]\n|birth_name    = \n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|1905|6|5}}\n|birth_place   = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|1971|2|2|1905|6|5}}\n|death_place   = Chicago, Illinois\n|resting_place = [[All Saints Cemetery|All Saints Catholic Cemetery and Mausoleum]], [[Des Plaines, Illinois]]\n|profession    = Attorney\n|spouse        =  Katherine (d. 1961)<br/>Iris McCreevey\n|children      = 3\n|education     = [[DePaul University]] ({{small|[[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]]}})\n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n}}\n\n'''Edward Rowan Finnegan''' (June 5, 1905 &ndash; February 2, 1971) was an attorney and politician from [[Illinois]]. He served as a member of the  [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Illinois]] from 1961 to 1964 and a judge of the [[Illinois Circuit Court of Cook County|Circuit Court of Cook County]] from 1964 until his death.\n\n==Biography==\nFinnegan was born in Chicago and attended the parochial schools.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\">{{cite news |date=February 3, 1971 |title=Finnegan, Judge Here, Dies at 65 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41618912/chicago-tribune/ |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |location=Chicago, IL |page=24 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> He graduated from St. Rita High School, and attended [[Loyola University Chicago]] and [[Northwestern University Pritzker School of Law|Northwestern University Law School]].<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> Finnegan graduated from [[DePaul University]] with a  [[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]] degree in 1930.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> He was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] in 1931 and practiced in Chicago.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/>\n\nIn 1939, Finnegan unsuccessfully sought the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nomination for municipal court judge.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> In 1945, he was appointed an assistant [[state's attorney]] for [[Cook County, Illinois|Cook County]], and served until 1956.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> He served as an assistant city [[corporation counsel]] from 1956 to 1957.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/>\n\nIn 1960, Finnegan was elected to the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Illinois]]' 12th district.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> After redistricting, he was reelected from the 9th district in 1962.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> He served from January 1961 until resigning in December 1964.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> Finnegan ran in the newly-configured 9th district in 1962 because incumbent [[Sidney R. Yates]] won the Democratic nomination for U.S. Senator. In the general election, Yates was unsuccessful in his campaign against Republican incumbent [[Everett Dirksen]].\n\nFinnegan was renominated for the US House in April 1964. Later that month, he nearly drowned while swimming at the Lake Shore Club. A lifeguard administered cardiopulmonary resuscitation for several minutes before he regained consciousness, and he was hospitalized for several days.\n\nFinnegan decided later in 1964 that he preferred to serve as a judge, while Yates desired to return to the U.S. House. In October 1964, Finnegan resigned the U.S. House nomination. Yates was chosen as his replacement and easily won the November election.\n\nFinnegan was nominated for judge of the [[Illinois Circuit Court of Cook County|Circuit Court of Cook County]].<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> He won his November 1964 election, then resigned from Congress shortly before the expiration of his term.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> Finnegan served on the bench from December 1964 until his death.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/>\n\nFinnegan died at a Chicago hospital on February 2, 1971.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> He was buried at [[All Saints Cemetery|All Saints Catholic Cemetery and Mausoleum]] in [[Des Plaines, Illinois]].\n\n==Family==\nFinnegan's first wife, Katherine, died in 1961.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> They were the parents of three daughters -- Sara, Moira, and Kathleen.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> In 1964, Finnegan married Iris McCreevey, who survived him.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|F000135}}\n*{{Findagrave|7672162}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state = Illinois| district = 12| before= [[Charles A. Boyle]]| after = [[Robert McClory]]\n| years= January 3, 1961{{spaced ndash}}January 3, 1963\n}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state = Illinois| district = 9| before= [[Sidney R. Yates]]| after = [[Sidney R. Yates]]\n| years= January 3, 1963{{spaced ndash}}December 6, 1964\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finnegan, Edward Rowan}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Loyola University Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:DePaul University College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Illinois Democrats]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Illinois state court judges]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n\n\n{{Illinois-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{other people|Edward Finnegan}}\n{{no footnotes|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Edward Rowan Finnegan\n|image         = Edward Rowan Finnegan.jpg\n|caption       = \n|state1        = [[Illinois]]\n|district1     = {{ushr|Illinois|9|9th}}\n|term_start1   = January 3, 1963\n|term_end1     = December 6, 1964\n|predecessor1  = [[Sidney R. Yates]]\n|successor1    = [[Sidney R. Yates]]\n|state2        = [[Illinois]]\n|district2     = {{ushr|Illinois|12|12th}}\n|term_start2   = January 3, 1961\n|term_end2     = January 3, 1963\n|predecessor2  = [[Charles A. Boyle]]\n|successor2    = [[Robert McClory]]\n|birth_name    = \n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|1905|6|5}}\n|birth_place   = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|1971|2|2|1905|6|5}}\n|death_place   = Chicago, Illinois\n|resting_place = [[All Saints Cemetery|All Saints Catholic Cemetery and Mausoleum]], [[Des Plaines, Illinois]]\n|profession    = Attorney\n|spouse        =  Katherine (d. 1961)<br/>Iris McCreevey\n|children      = 3\n|education     = [[DePaul University]] ({{small|[[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]]}})\n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n}}\n\n'''Edward Rowan Finnegan''' (June 5, 1905 &ndash; February 2, 1971) was an attorney and politician from [[Illinois]]. He served as a member of the  [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Illinois]] from 1961 to 1964 and a judge of the [[Illinois Circuit Court of Cook County|Circuit Court of Cook County]] from 1964 until his death.\n\n==Biography==\nFinnegan was born in Chicago and attended the parochial schools.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\">{{cite news |date=February 3, 1971 |title=Finnegan, Judge Here, Dies at 65 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41618912/chicago-tribune/ |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |location=Chicago, IL |page=24 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> He graduated from St. Rita High School, and attended [[Loyola University Chicago]] and [[Northwestern University Pritzker School of Law|Northwestern University Law School]].<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> Finnegan graduated from [[DePaul University]] with a  [[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]] degree in 1930.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> He was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] in 1931 and practiced in Chicago.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/>\n\nIn 1939, Finnegan unsuccessfully sought the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nomination for municipal court judge.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> In 1945, he was appointed an assistant [[state's attorney]] for [[Cook County, Illinois|Cook County]], and served until 1956.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> He served as an assistant city [[corporation counsel]] from 1956 to 1957.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/>\n\nIn 1960, Finnegan was elected to the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Illinois]]' 12th district.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> After redistricting, he was reelected from the 9th district in 1962.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> He served from January 1961 until resigning in December 1964.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> Finnegan ran in the newly-configured 9th district in 1962 because incumbent [[Sidney R. Yates]] won the Democratic nomination for U.S. Senator, but lost the general election.\n\nFinnegan was renominated for the US House in April 1964. Later that month, he nearly drowned while swimming at the Lake Shore Club, and a lifeguard administered cardiopulmonary resuscitation for several minutes before he regained consciousness.\n\nFinnegan decided later in 1964 that he preferred to serve as a judge, while Yates desired to return to the U.S. House. In October 1964, Finnegan resigned the U.S. House nomination. Yates was chosen as his replacement and easily won the November election.\n\nFinnegan was nominated for judge of the [[Illinois Circuit Court of Cook County|Circuit Court of Cook County]].<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> He won his November 1964 election, then resigned from Congress shortly before the expiration of his term.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> Finnegan served on the bench from December 1964 until his death.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/>\n\nFinnegan died at a Chicago hospital on February 2, 1971.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> He was buried at [[All Saints Cemetery|All Saints Catholic Cemetery and Mausoleum]] in [[Des Plaines, Illinois]].\n\n==Family==\nFinnegan's first wife, Katherine, died in 1961.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> They were the parents of three daughters -- Sara, Moira, and Kathleen.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/> In 1964, Finnegan married Iris McCreevey, who survived him.<ref name=\"JudgeHere\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|F000135}}\n*{{Findagrave|7672162}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state = Illinois| district = 12| before= [[Charles A. Boyle]]| after = [[Robert McClory]]\n| years= January 3, 1961{{spaced ndash}}January 3, 1963\n}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state = Illinois| district = 9| before= [[Sidney R. Yates]]| after = [[Sidney R. Yates]]\n| years= January 3, 1963{{spaced ndash}}December 6, 1964\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finnegan, Edward Rowan}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Loyola University Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:DePaul University College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Illinois Democrats]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Illinois state court judges]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n\n\n{{Illinois-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Billmckern", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Rowan_Finnegan"}
{"title_page": "The Joker (1960 film)", "text_new": "{{About|the 1960 film||Joker}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Joker\n| image          = The Joker (1960).jpg\n| caption        = Original title French poster\n| director       = [[Philippe de Broca]]\n| producer       = [[Claude Chabrol]]<br>Roland Nonin\n| writer         = Philippe de Broca<br>[[Daniel Boulanger]]\n| starring       = [[Jean-Pierre Cassel]]<br>[[Anouk Aim\u00e9e]]\n| music          = [[Georges Delerue]]\n| cinematography = [[Jean Penzer]]\n| editing        = Laurence M\u00e9ry-Clark\n| distributor    = Les Films Fernand Rivers, Guamont\n| released       = {{film date|1960|8||df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 88 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''The Joker''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Le Farceur'''}}) is a 1960 French [[comedy film]] directed by [[Philippe de Broca]].\n\n==Plot==\nEdouard Berlon is a young, incorrigible seducer who moves very lightly from one affair to the next. He meets Helene Larouch, a woman married to Andr\u00e9, a rich financier who is very busy with his affairs, leaving her in an emotionally arid life. Initially Helene resists Edouard's wooing, but as she gets to know his lively character, his eccentric lifestyle and his very unusual family environment, including his old uncle Th\u00e9odose, his brother Pilou, servat Olga, some infants, and a few stray dogs, she lets herself become seduced. Their relation, however, turns out to be an ephemeral one as Edouard is busy seducing another woman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unifrance.org/film/1741/le-farceur#synopsis |title=Le Farceur |work=unifrance.org |language=French |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinema.encyclopedie.films.bifi.fr/index.php?pk=51886 |title=Le Farceur > R\u00e9sum\u00e9  |work=cinema.encyclopedie.films.bifi.fr |accessdate=27 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsdefrance.com/review/le-farceur-1961.html |title=Le Farceur (1961) |author=James Travers |work=filmsdefrance.com |accessdate=27 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Anouk Aim\u00e9e]] as Helene Larouch\n* [[Jean-Pierre Cassel]] as Edouard Berlon\n* [[Pierre Palau]] as Th\u00e9odose\n* [[Genevi\u00e8ve Cluny]] as Pilou Berlon\n* [[Georges Wilson]] as Guillaume Berlon\n* Anne Tonietti as Olga\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois Maistre]] as Andr\u00e9 Laroche\n* Jean-Pierre Rambal as Paul\n* Liliane Patrick as Solange\n* Ir\u00e8ne Chabrier as Aline, servant at the inn\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its premiere at the [[Locarno Festival|Locarno Film Festival]] in August 1960, but was not released commercially until 20 January 1961 in France and 7 August 1961 in New York. During the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]], the film was presented with other classics at the Cin\u00e9ma de la Plage,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/69-editions/retrospective/2012/selection/cinema-de-la-plage |title=Cinema de la Plage 2012 |work=festival-cannes.com |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> a non-competitive part of the official selection that is open to the public. In 12 November 2013, the film was presented at the [[Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que qu\u00e9b\u00e9coise]], [[Montr\u00e9al]].<ref name=\"cinemateque\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cinematheque.qc.ca/en/programmation/projections/film/farceur?pid=16375 |title=Projections - Le Farceur |work=cinematheque.qc.ca |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Critical response==\nThe film has been described as \"a lot of genial fun\" as the plot evolves. It also has been described as whimsical and in parts \"nutty\" for the eccentric lifestyle of the hero and his family.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9D0CE2DD123BE13ABC4053DFBE66838A679EDE |title=Screen: Whimsical French Comedy:Joker' Has Premiere at 2 Theatres Here Jean-Pierre Cassel in the Leading Role |author=Bosley Crowther |date=8 August 1961 |work=nytimes.com |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> French critics, on the other hand, find subtle qualities in the presentation of the characters as uncle Th\u00e9odose is described as \"an original, old uncle\" as well as poetic connotations in the overall work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telerama.fr/cinema/films/le-farceur,24229,critique.php |title=Le farceur |author=Aur\u00e9lien Ferenczi |date=6 July 2013 |language=French |work=telerama.fr |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senscritique.com/film/Le_Farceur/critique/24240793 |title=Avis sur le film Le Farceur |work=senscritique.com |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0053814|title=The Joker}}\n\n{{Philippe de Broca}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joker, The}}\n[[Category:1961 films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:1960s romantic comedy films]]\n\n\n{{1960s-France-film-stub}}\n{{romantic-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Joker\n| image          = The Joker (1960).jpg\n| caption        = Original title French poster\n| director       = [[Philippe de Broca]]\n| producer       = [[Claude Chabrol]]<br>Roland Nonin\n| writer         = Philippe de Broca<br>[[Daniel Boulanger]]\n| starring       = [[Jean-Pierre Cassel]]<br>[[Anouk Aim\u00e9e]]\n| music          = [[Georges Delerue]]\n| cinematography = [[Jean Penzer]]\n| editing        = Laurence M\u00e9ry-Clark\n| distributor    = Les Films Fernand Rivers, Guamont\n| released       = {{film date|1960|8||df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 88 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''The Joker''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Le Farceur'''}}) is a 1960 French [[comedy film]] directed by [[Philippe de Broca]].\n\n==Plot==\nEdouard Berlon is a young, incorrigible seducer who moves very lightly from one affair to the next. He meets Helene Larouch, a woman married to Andr\u00e9, a rich financier who is very busy with his affairs, leaving her in an emotionally arid life. Initially Helene resists Edouard's wooing, but as she gets to know his lively character, his eccentric lifestyle and his very unusual family environment, including his old uncle Th\u00e9odose, his brother Pilou, servat Olga, some infants, and a few stray dogs, she lets herself become seduced. Their relation, however, turns out to be an ephemeral one as Edouard is busy seducing another woman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unifrance.org/film/1741/le-farceur#synopsis |title=Le Farceur |work=unifrance.org |language=French |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinema.encyclopedie.films.bifi.fr/index.php?pk=51886 |title=Le Farceur > R\u00e9sum\u00e9  |work=cinema.encyclopedie.films.bifi.fr |accessdate=27 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsdefrance.com/review/le-farceur-1961.html |title=Le Farceur (1961) |author=James Travers |work=filmsdefrance.com |accessdate=27 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Anouk Aim\u00e9e]] as Helene Larouch\n* [[Jean-Pierre Cassel]] as Edouard Berlon\n* [[Pierre Palau]] as Th\u00e9odose\n* [[Genevi\u00e8ve Cluny]] as Pilou Berlon\n* [[Georges Wilson]] as Guillaume Berlon\n* Anne Tonietti as Olga\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois Maistre]] as Andr\u00e9 Laroche\n* Jean-Pierre Rambal as Paul\n* Liliane Patrick as Solange\n* Ir\u00e8ne Chabrier as Aline, servant at the inn\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its premiere at the [[Locarno Festival|Locarno Film Festival]] in August 1960, but was not released commercially until 20 January 1961 in France and 7 August 1961 in New York. During the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]], the film was presented with other classics at the Cin\u00e9ma de la Plage,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/69-editions/retrospective/2012/selection/cinema-de-la-plage |title=Cinema de la Plage 2012 |work=festival-cannes.com |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> a non-competitive part of the official selection that is open to the public. In 12 November 2013, the film was presented at the [[Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que qu\u00e9b\u00e9coise]], [[Montr\u00e9al]].<ref name=\"cinemateque\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cinematheque.qc.ca/en/programmation/projections/film/farceur?pid=16375 |title=Projections - Le Farceur |work=cinematheque.qc.ca |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Critical response==\nThe film has been described as \"a lot of genial fun\" as the plot evolves. It also has been described as whimsical and in parts \"nutty\" for the eccentric lifestyle of the hero and his family.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9D0CE2DD123BE13ABC4053DFBE66838A679EDE |title=Screen: Whimsical French Comedy:Joker' Has Premiere at 2 Theatres Here Jean-Pierre Cassel in the Leading Role |author=Bosley Crowther |date=8 August 1961 |work=nytimes.com |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> French critics, on the other hand, find subtle qualities in the presentation of the characters as uncle Th\u00e9odose is described as \"an original, old uncle\" as well as poetic connotations in the overall work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telerama.fr/cinema/films/le-farceur,24229,critique.php |title=Le farceur |author=Aur\u00e9lien Ferenczi |date=6 July 2013 |language=French |work=telerama.fr |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senscritique.com/film/Le_Farceur/critique/24240793 |title=Avis sur le film Le Farceur |work=senscritique.com |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0053814|title=The Joker}}\n\n{{Philippe de Broca}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joker, The}}\n[[Category:1961 films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:1960s romantic comedy films]]\n\n\n{{1960s-France-film-stub}}\n{{romantic-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ikjbagl", "label": "safe", "comment": "adding disambiguation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Joker_(1960_film)"}
